replies.comment info:
@Obedson R 

If both parties had equal representation in a district, then that districts vote is determined by an extremely small population. Politicians do not need to convince the members of their party to vote, far right and far left voters will always vote for their color, instead they need to convince the 10% in the middle. In a district, 10% of the people can decide an election. That is such a small amount of people.
 There is not really a right way to go about making districts with political parties at the forefront of our decision making.

@Ana 

Hello Ana. Thanks for participating today. You mention what is fair or unfair to the party in your response.  Do you think districts should be drawn to be fair to a political party or to the people?  Or do you think they are the same thing?  

Congressional districts are made up of about 700,000 people.  Since there is no easy way to ask all of them, what do you think is the best way to make sure each of their votes count?

@Miles 

Hello Miles!  Thanks for checking out the graph today.  

Do you think the districts were created arbitrarily or manipulated?   Perhaps there is one of each?  Do you think a person's vote means more in one of these graphs than another?  Is there a way to make everyone's vote matter?

@Bidipta Roy 

You have some interesting wonderings here.  You say, "Since it [gerrymandering] gives one party a political advantage, then either the democratic  or republican party is corrupt and could determine which party controls a part of the government."  And that is definitely possible. Letting those in power draw the redistricting map is often a recipe for a map drawn to benefit those in power the most.

It is not the majority but some states do not let political parties draw the map.  I wonder what the process is in your state?

@Lindsay Simcich 

Hello Lindsay.  I find your title interesting.  Which of these dots do you think represent, 'the forgotten votes?"

You are correct to mention the census.  It is the tool that all states uses to create their congressional districts.  Are the district lines in Wisconsin changing?
